<TITLE> Climate most daunting global challenge: Hasina </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Jul 16 (bdnews24.com)Prime minister Sheikh Hasina highlighted climate change, security concerns and the global financial crisis in her address Wednesday to the Non-Aligned Movement summit at the Egyptian resort city of Sharm El-Shaikh,. "I believe climate change remains as one of the most daunting global challenges of our time," Hasina told the gathering of state and government leaders from around the world. She said Bangladesh, as a least developed country and situated in a low-lying delta, remained deeply concerned with the impact of global warming. "A perceptible rise in sea level would submerge a third of the country," she said. Hasina said concerns of least developed countries were often bypassed in the global debate, and it was vital that greater attention was paid to them at the upcoming climate change meet in Copenhagen. She said global peace and security also remain one of NAM's overriding concerns. She said Bangladesh was proud of its record as one of the top contributors to the international peace keeping force. "Bangladesh denounces terrorism in all its forms and manifestations," said Hasina. She said her administration had proposed establishment of a South Asian Task Force on Counter Terrorism, and was now working with regional partners to realise the project. Turning to the global economic recession, Hasina said the most vulnerable countries stood to suffer the most, although they had not contributed significantly to the problem. "An unfair international financial structure has, to a large extent, contributed to this situation," she said. She said developed countries should deliver on key issues such as duty- and quota-free market access as well as trade capacity building to 
